<h1 class="hero-h">A 10-criteria AI vendor <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">evaluation framework.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">When every vendor's deck says "AI-powered," buying becomes harder, not easier. This is a 10-criteria scorecard we use to evaluate AI vendors for B2B clients — covering both the AI claims and the boring fundamentals that matter more than the AI.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">How to use this framework</span><h2 class="h2">Score and compare</h2><p class="body">For each shortlisted vendor, score each of the 10 criteria 1-5. Total possible: 50. Anything under 35 is a probable no. 35-42 is a worth-piloting. 43+ is a strong candidate. Use the comments column to capture deal-specific notes.</p><div class="callout"><p>The two most-skipped criteria — and the two that most often kill rollouts — are #6 (data handling specifics) and #10 (real total cost). Spend extra time there.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The scorecard</span><h2 class="h2">10 criteria with scoring rubrics</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Criterion</th><th>What 5/5 looks like</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Specific use-case fit</strong></td><td>Vendor can describe 3 customers like you who solved your specific problem with their tool, with measurable outcomes.</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Underlying model quality</strong></td><td>Vendor uses a current frontier model (Claude, GPT-4 class, or current Gemini). Disclosed which model and version, with rationale.</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Workflow integration depth</strong></td><td>Native integration into the systems you already use (CRM, ticketing, email). Not just "export to CSV."</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td><strong>Customization &amp; control</strong></td><td>You can edit prompts, add knowledge, tune behavior. Not a sealed black box.</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td><strong>Reliability &amp; output quality</strong></td><td>You ran a real pilot on your data. Quality met or exceeded what your team produces.</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td><strong>Data handling</strong></td><td>Documented: where data is stored, who can access it, whether it trains models, retention period, deletion rights. SOC 2 / ISO 27001 attestations provided.</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td><strong>Support &amp; onboarding</strong></td><td>Named CSM, documented onboarding plan, response SLAs in writing. Not just email-only.</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td><strong>Pricing transparency</strong></td><td>Pricing is clear, predictable, and scales reasonably. No surprise per-token billing or hidden usage fees.</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td><strong>Roadmap fit</strong></td><td>Vendor roadmap aligns with where your needs are heading. Quarterly release cadence visible.</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td><strong>Total cost of ownership</strong></td><td>Includes: license, implementation, training, internal admin time, integration build, and likely future expansion. Realistic 3-year view.</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Deeper questions to ask</span><h2 class="h2">What to ask in vendor demos</h2><h3 class="h3">On the AI substance</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Which model powers this? What version? When do you update?</li><li>What guardrails prevent the model from producing harmful or off-brand output?</li><li>How do you handle hallucinations? What is your accuracy claim grounded in?</li><li>Can we see the system prompt, or at least edit ours?</li></ul><h3 class="h3">On data &amp; security</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Does our data train your models? Or any third-party model?</li><li>Where is our data stored geographically? Can we choose?</li><li>Who at your company can read our data? Under what circumstances?</li><li>What happens to our data if we churn?</li><li>Provide your SOC 2 report, DPA, and BAA (if applicable).</li></ul><h3 class="h3">On real production use</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Who are 3 customers using this exactly the way we would? Can we talk to them?</li><li>What is your typical implementation timeline for a team like ours?</li><li>What percentage of your customers churn in year 1? Why?</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Red flags</span><h2 class="h2">When to walk</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Vague answers about the underlying model.</strong> If they cannot tell you what's under the hood, they have either built thinly on top or they are obscuring it.</li><li><strong>No real customers in your stage or industry.</strong> You will pay for their learning curve.</li><li><strong>Cannot produce a SOC 2 report.</strong> Acceptable for an early-stage tool only if you are not putting real data in.</li><li><strong>Pricing they will not put in writing.</strong> Means the price is whatever they can negotiate.</li><li><strong>"You will not need to change your workflow."</strong> Real AI deployment always requires workflow change. If they say otherwise, they are selling a layer that will not be used.</li></ul></div></section>

